    H range: 14
    Lipschitz / range ratio: 0.8571
    → Each arc flip perturbs H by at most 85.7% of range

======================================================================
  TURBO CODE ANALOGY VIA CYCLE OVERLAP
======================================================================

  TURBO DECODING ANALOGY:

  Noisy comparisons → [Score decoder] → ĉ₃ (robust, 85% of info)
                     ↕ (soft info via OCF constraints)
                     → [5-cycle decoder] → ĉ₅ (refines, 97% of info)
                     ↕ (rigid constraint at n=7: c₅ + 2·disj₃₃ = 56)
                     → [7-cycle decoder] → ĉ₇ (completes, 100%)

  Key: The rigid constraint c₅ + 2·disj₃₃ = const is an
  ERROR-CORRECTING PARITY CHECK on the cycle spectrum!

  NOISY COMPARISON SIMULATION (n=5):
  Flip each arc independently with probability p_flip
    p_flip=0.00: RMSE(H)=0.00, mean |Δscore|=0.00
    p_flip=0.05: RMSE(H)=2.64, mean |Δscore|=0.65
    p_flip=0.10: RMSE(H)=3.93, mean |Δscore|=1.08
    p_flip=0.20: RMSE(H)=5.01, mean |Δscore|=1.66
    p_flip=0.30: RMSE(H)=5.44, mean |Δscore|=2.02

======================================================================
  MUTUAL INFORMATION CHAIN (FOURIER LAYERS)
======================================================================

  Mutual Information Chain Rule:
    I(H; score)          = 2.2849 bits (85.2%)
    I(H; c5 | score)     = 0.3962 bits (14.8%)
    I(H; rest | sc, c5)  = 0.000000 bits (0.0%)
    Total                = 2.6810 bits

  Information per computation cost:
    Score: O(n²) = O(25) → 2.2849 bits → 0.0914 bits/op
    5-cycles: O(n⁵) = O(3125) → 0.3962 bits → 0.000127 bits/op

  Score extraction is 721× more efficient per bit!

======================================================================
  WYNER-ZIV: RATE-DISTORTION WITH SIDE INFORMATION
======================================================================

  WYNER-ZIV SCENARIO:

  Alice observes tournament T → wants to communicate H(T)
  Bob has side information: score sequence of T

  Direct rate:    H(H) = 2.6810 bits
  With side info: H(H|score) = 0.3962 bits
  Saving:         I(H;score) = 2.2849 bits (85.2%)

  WYNER-ZIV GAIN: Alice saves 85.2% even without knowing
  that Bob has scores! This is because score and H are NOT independent
  of the coding scheme — they share the SAME underlying tournament.

  PRACTICAL APPLICATION: In distributed ranking systems (e.g., peer review),
  different reviewers see overlapping subsets. The score-based estimator
  acts as "free" side information available to all nodes.

